      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"color:black;font-size:12.0pt;\">A 30-year-old male presents with high-grade fever and chills. He has a travel history. His pulse rate is noted to be relatively slower than what would be expected for his fever. In which of the following conditions is relative bradycardia uncommon?</span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q8277633",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 35750,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        6
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Ans. D. Factitious fever</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option D:&nbsp;</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Relative bradycardia</strong>, also known as <strong>Faget's sign </strong>(a lower-than-expected heart rate given the high body temperature), is <strong>uncommon In Factitious fever.&nbsp;</strong></span><br>&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>In factitious fever (fever artificially induced or faked), the pulse is usually normal or exaggerated for the supposed fever, and many physiological signs don't match the claimed symptoms.</strong></span><br>&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Explanation:</u></strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option A. Brucellosis:&nbsp;</strong>Can present with <strong>relative bradycardia.</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option B. Typhoid:&nbsp;</strong>Known to show <strong>relative bradycardia.</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option C. </strong>Yes, can sometimes present with relative bradycardia, especially <strong>Plasmodium falciparum</strong> during febrile spikes.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Educational Objective:</u></strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Relative bradycardia </strong>is seen in <strong>typhoid fever</strong>, <strong>Legionnaire’s disease</strong>, <strong>Scrub typhus </strong>and <strong>Chlamydia, Babesia, Brucellosis, Rickettsial infections, Ebola/Marburg virus</strong>, <strong>dengue</strong>, <strong>yellow fever </strong>and <strong>non-infectious cases </strong>such as <strong>CNS lesions </strong>(central fever), <strong>lymphoma </strong>and <strong>Drug Fever</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Ref:&nbsp;</u>Apurba Sastry’s Essentials of Med. Microbiology 2/e p660&nbsp;</strong></span></p>",
